Title: search PATH for avrdude on linux based systems
Body: As a variation on the fix for issue #96 I wrote a detector for avrdude based on the PATH variable. This can work on any Linux (or Mac) system as long as de folder that contains avrdude is in the PATH variable. On Windows systems this will not work out of the box sins Windows uses a semicolon in stead of a colon as a separator in the PATH variable but this could be detected. I saw that the original issue was solved already  but I wanted to share this because it can be of use for people that have avrdude in a non standard location. I they put that location in PATH then this will work out of the box.

Title: AlsaAudio driver
Body: I create this pull request even though it is a little bit bigger. I building a armhf based groundstation and decide to use apm_planner because it can run native under linux. after first try I noticed that there was no audio available.  on looking into code I see that phonon was commented in gaudiooutput class. if activating phonon  I see that phonon crashed if application will closed and gaudiooutput destructor is called. trying to find out what goes wrong ended with no concrete results. next I try qgroundstation which of course also use phonon. same result it crash on destructor. I never test qgroundstation or apmplanner on other systems than linux. thats  why i do not know if audio is available there. also i do not know if audio is an feature of interest for apm_planner. if yes  maybe this pull request can be interesting for the project(linux only).  the request contains - a simple alsa driver implemented as QThread - small improvement in UAS.cc to message battery current in percent as audio message. - small change in gaudiooutput. now the soundfiles which are created from flite speak synthesiser are not temporally any more. now they will stored in an extra directory in ~/apmplanner2/tmp_audio. all files named by spoken content.  this is no problem because the files are not so big. mostly between  20 - 60kib. the goal here is that flite step will skipped if file already exist. this will save cpu load and reduce write access to storage. interesting for small embedded systems with low cpu and sdcard based storage. because wav files no longer temporally  it is also possible to queue messages. at least this was needed mostly for the QThread AlsaDriver. if files temporally created and erased in main thread there was no possibility from QThread AlsaDriver to successfully open them.  ok  long text  short info:)  new dependences: libasound libsndfile  I try to use  persistent platform independent settings which are defined in QSettings. so hopefully there are no problems to build and execute on other systems. of course without alsa driver and improvements. at least I have not the possibility here to build&test on windows and osx systems.  /g wolke

Title: Fix to undo tautological code
Body: You need to explicitly cast (-1) to be uint8_t or else the compiler will realize that the LHS of the if can never be -1 and will just remove the if statement.

Title: Better battery calcs
Body: Some changes to how battery time-remaining is calculated under fluctuating readings. - First  use low-pass filtered voltage for the calculations - Second  do not rely on the first voltage reading above -1.0V as being definitive.  In practice I sometimes see that initial reading be way low  leading to screwy calculations.  Instead  now any time I see a higher voltage  we reset startVoltage.  As I'm typing this note  I'm thinking that actually you could potentially get a really big spiky high voltage  which would screw things up too.  But this is I think at least better than the current system.  Ideally actually we'd keep a rolling window to do better estimation based on recent power consumption  rather than estimate future power consumption based on all of history  which history likely includes a power-sucking takeoff which won't actually likely recur during the rest of the flight...

Title: Broadcast estimated battery time remaining
Body: Use better  more useful numbers when broadcasting battery info in QuickView -- use filtered charge level estimate and battery voltage  and also broadcast estimated charge time remaining.

Title: Changed the way APMPlanner2 handles looking for support files to be more
Body: Program can now handle the support files being in ../share/APMPlanner2 on Linux. A number of changes were required throughout the program to point to a single routine in configuration.h QGC::shareDirectory()  whose purpose is to return the location of the support files.  This way Linux won't need hacky shortcuts in the /bin directory  making the installation process easier/safer.  It seems that the merge from qgroundcontrol last week "Cleaned up build files (inline with QGC changes 34c2c3d980)" inadvertently removed some of my build changes from two weeks ago  by unincluding qgroundcontrol.pri in the build process. I've put those changes in QGCSetup.pri instead.

Title: Triple layout PFD
Body: Hi  here is what we talked about. A PFD that can live with just about any aspect ratio. If somebody has a better idea for the tall'n'narrow layout with the 4 panels around the compass  let me hear. We probably do not want it to show more information in one layout than in the others - that could really annoy people who want to see the info that sometimes gets hidden. But showing it better in some sense when there is more space is ok. Still needs lots of data/signal integration work. Some quantities like airspeed vs. groundspeed need be be cleanly separated. Needs an aesthetic cleanup too but at least the code design is not fouled  ie. it is possible.

Title: Fix log pull
Body: I noticed trying to pull logs with ArduCopter 3.2 was mostly unreliable. Changed the line handling so it waits until it sees the first line that _should_ be in a log file before starting to collect lines to write to the log file  and keeps collecting until it sees the "Logs]" line. This seems hack-ish and perhaps there's a more deterministic way to read logs  but this is the best I came up with. Please try it and verify it works for you. Thanks.

Title: QtGStreamer support for displaying video in the QML QtQuick 2 version of the PFD
Body: This branch has experimental code for using QtGStreamer to stream media (video/audio) to a Qt QML or QWidget. The code contains changes for the 'PrimaryFlightDisplayQML' and the 'HUD' (highly experimental) version of the flight display.   There is a dependency on QtGStreamer  GStreamer.  (http://gstreamer.freedesktop.org/modules/qt-gstreamer.html) This version was compiled with GStreamer 1.4.3 and QtGStreamer 0.10.1 QtGStreamer also has a dependency on Boost.    These dependences were not added to QMake. If it's decided to pull this code  the make files will need to include dependency checks for theses libs.

Title: joystick widget don t use operator which isn t present in Qt5
Widget Joystick
Body: Revive joystick code -- more of a re-implementation really. See #144.  Configure your joystick through the joystick menu. Activate the joystick (so it sends events to the UAS) by clicking on the joystick name.  If the UAS is a multi-rotor in stabilize mode  the joystick controls are sent as RC overrides  otherwise if the UAS is in manual mode the joystick controls are sent as manual controls.

Title: Comms Adding background connection detection to TCPLink as server
Body: Once started the TCPLink (as server) will continue to listen for incoming connection  and accepts them. Previously new connections would only be accepted when the connect button of the CommConfigurationWindow was clicked. This makes TCPLink (as server) work very much like the UDPLink  and more importantly makes it a lot easier to use.

Title: Comm reset base_mode custom_mode status on connection lost
Body: If the link with the UAS is lost  receivedMode is turned to false. Yet when the link is regained and the HEARTBEAT message is received (with the same base_mode) receivedMode will stay false and prevent UAS::setMode() from sending mode update to the UAS.  I am not sure this PR is the correct or best one  but it does address the issue.

Title: Master qt4
Body: Please ignore the readme since I made it specific to 12.04 Ubuntu with QT4 with qreal compiled as double on an ARM board.   I had to make changes to the Freenect files in order to compile with freenect support.  # include libfreenect/libfreenect.h wouldn't find the file but # include libfreenect.h worked.  Also  Freenect.cc depends on QGC object which is not included. I don't believe this change is specific to ARM boards but it is worth noting.

Title: Experimental Qt5 Code reduction and streamlined compass calibration
Body: Although I rebased this one on top of master  it should probably go into the Qt5-Wip branch  if at all. It's big and kind of unwieldily  but it packs a lot of punch: it represents a few things that I wanted to fix on the Qt5 side: - Improve compile times - Reduce warnings - Streamline the calibration process to not use message boxes.  In particular  this boiled down to the following...  There's a gazillion of warnings coming from the Eigen and AlgLib libraries. Those libraries also use templates very heavily and are in my opinion one of the reasons why the compile times are so long. So I tried to find out exactly which parts needed those "light-weight" (in my opinion  excessive use of templates is heavy-weight) libraries. It turns out that the Eigen library boils down to a single quaternion rotation to translate a frame of reference into another. The AlgLib library is used only for the compass calibration to perform a least squares reduction of the calibration data. So I refactored out the vector/quaternion stuff and added the least squares reduction into that mix too. It still needs the least squares stuff  but at least now it is in a re-usable Vertex3D API. The Eigen library however has left the building. My benchmarks showed a 8% speed increase in total compilation time. I'm sure there's more to found  but this is a start.  Since I was at the compass calibration page already  I figured I'd try to get rid of the modal progress box and the confirmation box. In my opinion  they are distracting and don't help with the flow of a calibration. So I changed the calibration to have those fields (a progress bar and some status) right there on the field. I also re-arranged some of the controls  fixed the hyperlink to actually open the magnetic declination page and generally aligned and stacked and resized things  so that they look good in a variety of screen resolutions. If the resolution is too small  it now even pops up a nice scrollbar.  So  long story short: try it out and give me some feedback - I don't expect this to go straight into production though.

Title: Dont use QObjects in different threads fix 802
Body: This code is experimental and by no means should be merged to master: it still has bugs ( mainly  it broke the connect / disconnect buttons ).  The code added in 20f7b8f to workaround a Qt bug also created a new issue: it constantly changed the thread that an object was created without paying attention about the signal / slot connection nor the thread ownership.  This code moves all object creation from within the UDPLink object inside the UDPLink thread  and the communication for the thread contol is done via boolean flags (_restart  _reconnect  _finish  etc ) that the thread mainloop will certainly hit and do what is requested.  Tested and there is no more crash because of broken UDP content  unfortunatelly it also broke the interface buttons for connection / disconnection  but that's easily fixable.  Signed-off-by: Tomaz Canabrava tomaz.canabrava@intel.com

Title: Dont use QObjects in different threads fix 802
Body: The code added in 20f7b8f to workaround a Qt bug also created a new issue: it constantly changed the thread that an object was created without paying attention about the signal / slot connection nor the thread ownership.  This code moves all object creation from within the UDPLink object inside the UDPLink thread  and the communication for the thread contol is done via boolean flags (_restart  _reconnect  _finish  etc ) that the thread mainloop will certainly hit and do what is requested.  Since a single approach is usually better than two different approaches because it's easier to spot a bug and fix it  I removed the BROKEN_SIGNAL define that was used to create two very different approaches of the code and used only the code that should work for the BROKEN_SIGNAL case  since it also should work for the non-broken signal ones.  Tested and there is no more crash because of broken UDP content  connection and disconnection of the UDP link works  no more random crashes on linux because of threads and UDP connection.  Signed-off-by: Tomaz Canabrava tomaz.canabrava@intel.com

Title: Reduced warnings emitted from Eigen
Body: Hi all  Compiling the APM-Planner on Linux (ubuntu 14.10) shows round about 2043 warnings. I dont  think its really critical but we should do something about that cause nobody will pay any attention to warnings anymore nor will even recognise when producing them.  In my opinion warning free compilation leads to better code quality and so should be a goal of development. So I tried to do something to reduce warnings. The Eigen lib is the worst part as the programmer of the lib knows by himself he created an special include to supress warnings while his library is included. This special include does not provide the warning supression for the GCC. So I extended the precompiler code to support GCC too reducing the warnings to 1007 on my ubuntu. Yes I know its not a good way to reduce warnings by supressing them  but it is an external lib and not maintained by the apm_planner people so the changes made to that code should be as small as possible. Sure the way rolandbosa invented is the better one  he removed the eigen lib code completely  but unfortunately nobody was able to check his code for correctness.  Okay some details about the changes measured on Ubuntu 14.10  QTcreator 3.1.1  gcc 4.9.1 Changes of precompiler code -> reduces warnings from 2043 to 1007 removing the RealScalar type -> reduces warnings from 1007 to 880  greetings from Hamburg

Title: Graph View Support for plotting data vs time if all data has microsec timestamp
Body: All data in Graph View is plotted against an artificial data index. This is a robust solution as not all logs support a valid time-line but it makes data matching against flight time impossible.  Since arducopter 3.3 all bin logs have a microsec time stamp on every value. So I thought it should be possible to plot the data vs. time and not only vs. index if the log has a valid time-line. After a lot of work (you know the first feature prototype takes only 20% of the time the whole feature takes) I have made it. if there is a valid time-line you can switch between time or index on x axis  if not the check-box for switching is hidden.  I made 2 screenshots where you can see nearly the same data. First one shows data vs. time and the second shows data vs. index. The plot vs. time looks far better and more natural. ![timeline](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7621911/12518273/f1595598-c137-11e5-85b1-627cd77370c5.png) ![timeline2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7621911/12518302/2a4fe04c-c138-11e5-9612-05f068dc40f1.png)  Changes overview: - Added checkbox to switch between data vs. time and data vs. index - Added several helper functions to avoid code doubling - Fixed crash on load log canceling - Removed some mem leaks - Extended AP2DataPlot2DModel to support time indexes - Cleanup and commenting

Title: Graph MOD MODE mode and vertical drag zoom
Body: Here's another  rather big commit  which brings the following features: - Updated to the latest version of QCustomPlot (V1.2.1) - Added the plotting of the MOD.MODE field. This will show up as strings like "STABILIZE"  "LOITER" in the graph at the appropriate time. This is a partial fix for #110  full for #233 and #241  I think. - Added a way to drag and zoom more than just the horizontal (time) axis:   *\* Now you can 'select' a graph and drag it horizontally _and_ vertically. Using the mouse wheel  will also zoom in both directions.   *\* Now you can select the axis on the far left (or the numbers  or the label of the data series being plotted) and use the mouse to drag it vertically and the mouse wheel to zoom it vertically. This will not affect the horizontal axes or all the other displayed axes (if you display more than one). - Added a "big" statistics box (currently available by double-clicking a graph). This box will show the data of the currently _visible_ part of the box. This allows you to zoom/drag away the "bad" parts of a log and get data relevant to what is just visible on the screen. For example  this works beautifully to find out the true average of ThrIn  when trying to calibrate hovering throttle. Or to find out the standard deviation of AccZ  when trying to reduce vibrations. Remember - _visible_ part only.  Unfortunately  there are some bugs in there still. Every now and then things crash. Especially when one turns on "Show value under cursor". Also  the whole grouping of axes into GroupA/B/C/D might not play well with text-based data like the MODE data series... There's some weird stuff in there that I don't understand just yet.

The proposed change should include a new #define that excludes these changes if GStreamer and QtGStreamer are not installed. This will required a change to the make files (not done here). This feature is especially interesting to FPV flyers and enables both normal analog video and HD video to be overlayed with flight data.  To use the feature  a binary install of GStreamer is needed on the local machine. These are available from the GStreamer.freedesktop.org website.  In APM Planner  the 'Settings' must be set to enable GStreamer and a valid GStreamer pipeline string set in the configuration. These settings are in the 'APM Planner' section of the configuration.

BUGFIX Datamodel now accepts FMT inserts after data inserts Fixes 980
Body: This should fix it. It is a hack - but it works. The real problem is that the data model counts the index for the FMT messages and the parser counts the index for the data messages. Perhaps we should remove the index handling from the parser and make the index handling in the data model. I think the index is somehow an internal of the data model  so the parser should not know about. As I'm doing a complete re factoring of the parsers at the moment I will see if I can fix it during this task.

Title: Index fix for data model
Body: Hi all  after reverting my last hack cause it broke the tlog parsing here comes the next approach! The main issue was that the DB-index for FMT messages was generated by the datamodel and the DB-index for the data rows was generated by the parser. I migrated the index generation completely into the data model. The only drawback of this solution is a hard coded offset for the data rows. This means the data model can take max 500 FMT lines. If there are more it will generate an Index failure. I don't think this is a real issue as the binary logs only have a quint8 for the message ID which results in max 255 different FMT messages. So the offset of 500 should be big enough. The other solution - working without offset and let everything be dynamic - leads to the problem that if you receive FMT messages when already receiving data (which is normal in tlogs) your index increases without a dataline. In the default graph view the index is used on the X-axis. So an index increase without a dataline would lead to a gap in x-axis values. Therefore I thought an offset would be the better solution.

Title: Bugfix and some more Fixes 997
Body: Hi all   my new PR with a fix for #997 and some other goodies :smiley:   Messages with a datafield mismatch will be "repaired". This means if the number of datafields in a message does not match the number stored in its descriptor the message gets reconstructed. This is done by creating a new message based on the format stored in the descriptor which will be enriched with all valid data which can be found in the original message. Values that are missing will be set to zero and values which can not be collated are dropped. All repairings are logged with its index.

Body: While scanning the code I came across this particular memcpy()  which seems to use the wrong function to calculate the number of bytes to copy. The correct function to use is qMin()  to avoid the buffer overflow.  Also  according to the comments in the header file for the structure  it is ok to fill the field up to the very last byte and omit the terminating zero-byte. I didn't take the time to go into the details on the receiving side and validate that the comment actually is implemented. So to err on the safe side  this code still hardcodes a terminating zero-byte at the end of the name  just to make sure.  Lastly  this code compiles  but I haven't found a way to exercise it. Please review thoroughly.

Title: read and request int32 waypoints
Body: Hello APM Planner developers     I found a problem that the waypoints drawn on the map are not accurate. According to this post: https://discuss.ardupilot.org/t/inaccurate-waypoint-logging-with-toggle-switch/26636  I believed that the error come from the conversion from float to double value. APM Planner requests and write waypoints gps position  in float  however  the Ardupilot system uses int32 to store the gps position for waypoints in default. So I changed the source code to make APM Planner request and write each waypoints in int32. The message ID for the mission item  which contains waypoint ID  should be MAVLINK_MSG_ID_MISSION_ITEM_INT rather than the MAVLINK_MSG_ID_MISSION_ITEM  and the mission item type should be mavlink_mission_item_int_t instead of mavlink_mission_item_t.

Title: Added mission type to MAVLink mission_count message
Body: This pull request fixes the following bug:    While uploading the waypoints to the UAS  a `mission_count` message is sent. The struct `mavlink_mission_count_t` has a field `mission_type`  which was not set and therefore had a random value (so in most cases 0). You can find the possible values in [MAVLink's common.h](https://github.com/ArduPilot/apm_planner/blob/master/libs/mavlink/include/mavlink/v2.0/common/common.h#L664-L666). I set it to `MAV_MISSION_TYPE_MISSION`.    Best   Dino

Title: Allow MAV_CMD with values 255
Body: The new MAVLink version uses an [uint16 to store commands](https://github.com/ArduPilot/apm_planner/blob/master/libs/mavlink/include/mavlink/v2.0/common/mavlink_msg_mission_item.h#L16) (`MAV_CMD`). However  in the current master the value for commands is [limited to 255](https://github.com/ArduPilot/apm_planner/blob/master/src/ui/mission/QGCMissionOther.ui#L53). This pull request sets it to [the maximum allowable value](https://github.com/ArduPilot/apm_planner/blob/master/libs/mavlink/include/mavlink/v2.0/ardupilotmega/ardupilotmega.h#L215).

Title: Some Mavlink and serial communication improvements
Firmware Install Work around non instant modem availability for PX4
Body: During firmware updates  one is typically requested to replug the device.    On my system  the newly inserted device is nearly immediately detected by the planner  but the permissions on that device are not immediately set the right way (probably because `mtp-probe` needs to check it first). For this reason  firmware flashing is basically impossible.    This pull request introduces waiting for the device to become available with one-second sleeps between the attempts. While this is a dirty-ish hack  and something should have maybe done project-wide instead  I am not confident enough to do that. The introduced change just works for my use case  and is extremely unlikely to break anything.    This may probably fix #731  if I have guessed right which subsystem is responsible for that issue.
